> So, this is good because your question forces me to question the quick
> math I did on solar generation/crowbox consumption:
>
> An idle Crowbox pulls .235 watts of power, continuously. All day, and all
> night. Even though no birds visit at night, the Crowbox doesn't know what
> time it is, or that it has gotten dark.
>
> The solar panel I bought from Voltaic is a 2 watt panel. Solar panels
> notoriously deliver less energy than their rating so I figure I'll be
> pessimistic and assume we'll net 1 watt of power on average from the sola=
r
> panel in 'ordinary' daytime conditions. Even though winter time is hardly
> ordinary conditions.
>
> Where I live in northern Idaho, the winter 'days' are currently 7.5 hours
> long. Obviously, this is low southern sun. It seems to alternate, one sun=
ny
> winter day, one cloudy winter day, over and over. Less than ideal solar
> conditions, same as you.
>
> Some thumbnail math:
>
> Over 24 hours, a Crowbox consumes a total of 1200mAh.
>
> We (Idaho) currently have 16.5 hours of night. This means 825mAh consumed
> by the Crowbox during a time when the solar panel is pushing NO energy ba=
ck
> into the system.
>
> 2 watts is 400 mA at 5 volts. So 7.5 hours of daylight would generate
> 3000mAh *IF* the panel were delivering a full 2 watts of energy for a ful=
l
> 7.5 hours. NEITHER of which are going to happen in the winter.
>
> So, 1 watt is 200mA at 5 volts. 7.5 hours of daylight would generate
> 1500mAh if the panel averaged 1 watt of output over the 7.5 hours of
> 'daylight'. This might be pessimistic enough and accounts for better
> conditions during mid-day than just after sunrise and just before sunset,
> flattening to an average of 1 watt, continuous.
>
> If we could rely on the panel to deliver a full watt, a Crowbox would jus=
t
> keep on running. We'd be generating around 20% more energy than we requir=
e.
>
> Note that this doesn't account for ANY opening/closing of the Crowbox lid=
,
> so we can probably say that this activity could easily eat that extra 20%=
.
> Which would mean we're running with no effective margin of safety except
> the stored energy in the power bank.
>
> A 6,400mAh (rated) power bank from Voltaic would run a Crowbox for 72
> continuous hours on its own. If our panel/weather conditions underperform=
,
> we'd be losing an hour or two of that reserve juice each day. Which would
> still run a Crowbox for weeks.
>
> So it's a risk saying that this can be done with a 2 watt panel UNTIL we
> know exactly how much energy we are really getting from our panel. When m=
y
> 2W panel comes I'll hook it to an ammeter and get some precise output
> measurements under a couple of different conditions. Full, direct [winter=
]
> sun, and cloudy day.
>
> I wish we could turn off the Arduino UNO's power LED. I know we could
> reduce power consumption by 20% without that LED. The only way to turn it
> off is to take a razor and cut the trace on the Arduino's circuit board.
> Not something I'm comfortable pointing out to people.
>
> I still owe the project some research on SLEEP mode. I'll make some time
> to do that work. If it could mean users could save money by not requiring=
 a
> larger battery or larger solar panel, it's a meaningful feature.
>
> -Steve
>
